column8: Palo Alto Girls' Softball, formerly Palo Alto Bobby Sox, has been serving the greater Palo Alto community for more than 25 years. The organization, including the Board of Directors, is made entirely of volunteers, working hard behind the scenes to bring girls youth softball to Palo Alto. We currently support a spring recreation league for all girls ages 5 to 14, a summer "select" ASA tournament program, and a fall competitive program. In spring 2009, we placed approximately 400 girls with ages ranging from 5 to 14 years old on 30 - 40 teams in five divisions.

column8: Want to try crew? We're looking for girls & guys to join our competitive program. Bring our application form with your parent's signature, & try crew for a week. You'll love it! We are the original Palo Alto Crew Program; we've produced many athletes who received scholarships to some of the best college programs in the US. We have both Head Season and Sprint Season programs. No experience? No problem!

Looking for something new, fun, & different to try this summer?  Join NORCAL Crew for our weeklong "Learn to Row" sessions. Each session is open to boys & girls entering grades 7 - 12. No prior rowing experience required. Learn how to use our land training rowing machines, & spend time on the water learning how to row in our 60 foot long rowing shells. Sweep rowing (one oar per person in a 4-8 person boat) & sculling (2 oars per person in a one-person boat). If you're an 8th grader or High School athlete looking to try a new sport next year, try our summer program to see if you might want to try out next fall for our Novice Men or Women's competitive rowing teams. It's fun in the sun and on the water along the Bair Island preserve. Rowers will be coached by Olympians, World Champions and regionally & nationally ranked coaches.

column8:
endo, the “Way of the Sword,” is traditional Japanese Fencing. The Palo Alto Kendo Dojo is a volunteer-run organization practicing Kendo since 1987. Under experienced adult instruction, students learn strikes, footwork and strategies. Kendo uses shinai (bamboo sword) and bogu (protective armor) so that practitioners can safely exchange strikes. Kendo training is mentally and physically challenging. No previous martial arts experience required. Boys & girls age 7 and up are welcome.
Wednesdays, Gym, PA Buddhist Temple, 2751 Louis Road, 7:00-8:30 p.m.

column1: Stanford Lightning Youth Field Hockey Club
column8:
Stanford Lightning is a non-profit youth Field Hockey club designed to teach and promote field hockey to boys and girls ages 5-15.
We welcome players of ALL skill levels to join us and see if Stanford Lighting Youth Field Hockey is right for you.  We focus on skills and team building from beginners to experienced players. Your child will gain a solid understanding of the fundamentals in field hockey in a fun-filled and supportive environment. 
Stanford Lightning holds  practice all year long where players learn skills, build stamina and develop sportsmanship. There are tournaments throughout the year, but are mainly concentrated in the spring. If you want to try field hockey, drop by and join us in the fun.

column1: THE FIRST TEE OF SILICON VALLEY
column8:
The First Tee of Silicon Valley offers youth development through golf throughout Silicon Valley. As a Life Skills program, we build the character of youth to help them succeed in life. All 2nd through 12th graders, with or without golf experience, are eligible to join. Spring classes meet once per week, for eight lessons from mid March to mid May.
Palo Alto classes are held Tuesdays, 4 to 5:30 p.m., or Wednesdays, 2 to 3:30 p.m., at the Palo Alto Golf Course

column1: ICE SKATING AT THE WINTER LODGE
column8: Winter Lodge is a non-profit organization and has been teaching ice skating classes for kids for over 50 years here in Palo Alto. Fall, winter, & spring sessions.  The Fall session of classes begins the week of Sep 24. It includes a 1/2 hour group lesson once a week, with rental skates, free practice time, and 2 extra free practice passes for $184.00. Sign up in person, by phone, or by fax -- but when signups open, don't delay. Classes often fill up the first day!

At Paly, it's #2 in participation (behind only track; ahead of football, baseball, basketball, soccer, swimming). Spring Season 2012 -- boys' & girls' teams -- register [online] for new & returning players, beginner thru competitive: Boys Teams U9, U11, U13, & U15; Girls teams U11, U13, U15. Practices start in Feb; games, Mar-May.
Home games at Paly; we practice at various Palo Alto fields.

column4: Peninsula Youth Sailing Foundation - 1200 Chesapeake Dr -
column8: Our Racing Team is divided into two groups, the "Opti Green Team" and "Opti Race Team." Our Optimist racers are from 9-15 years old and enjoy improving their racing skills around the SF Bay Area and along the west coast. The Opti Green team is for sailors with less than a year sailing in Optimists, but who understand the basics of sailing and need an introduction to racing skills. The Opti Race team is for sailors who have experience racing Optimists around the Bay and are looking to refine racing skills.

column4: Peninsula Youth Sailing Foundation - 1200 Chesapeake Dr -
column8:
PYSF provides instruction, coaching, practice, and racing opportunities for Peninsula teens. Our mission is to coach, teach and nurture youth sailors in the San Francisco Bay Area. Many of the middle school and high school sailors in PYSF have developed into some of the top sailors in the US. We welcome all youth to come sail with us!

Our year-round sailing programs provide opportunities for kids of all ages to learn to sail and develop their sailing skills. Sailing is done in Optimists, Flying Juniors, 420's, and Lasers. Our sailors compete in regattas around the Bay, as well as up and down the West Coast. During the summer PYSF offers fun in-depth summer camps for boys and girls to learn to sail and race in small boats. There are also clinics for experienced sailors.

Since 1964 AYSO has been enriching children's lives with world-class soccer programs that promote a fun, family environment based on Six Philosophies:Everyone Plays,  Open Registration, Balanced Teams, Good, Sportsmanship, Positive Coaching, Player Development
More than 2000 Palo Alto kids and 450 Palo Alto parents work together each year to enrich our families and community. We produce soccer programs year-round from pre-kinder through high school, and a VIP program for special-needs kids. Our programs adjust field-size, skills training, tactical training, practice length and game length to match the developmental progress of each group. Older divisions play other Regions, Areas and Leagues.

column1:
PSV (PENINSULA SILICON VALLEY)
UNION FOOTBALL CLUB
column8: A non-profit youth soccer club based in Palo Alto, with professionally coached teams ages U7 to U18, & an Academy for ages 4-6. Our philosophy is based on a long term approach to development, focused on providing high level instruction & a great learning environment. Our teaching model is centered around year-round practice & play, an emphasis on repetition to master the fundamentals, & nurturing a dedication to learning and a love for the game. Our unique club environment, in which all teams, players & coaches collaborate so younger players can learn from more experienced players & older players in turn provide mentorship, helps promote player education. Our highly qualified & licensed coaches have played & coached around the world, and have many years of experience teaching all ages & levels. Most important, our coaches have a strong commitment to teaching & sharing their passion for the game. Players in our club range from 4 year old novices to 18 year old Youth National team players. We welcome various levels & experiences to come try out.

column1:
PSV (PENINSULA SILICON VALLEY) - Academy
UNION FOOTBALL CLUB
column8: SV Union Football Club's Academy focuses on introducing the game of soccer to the youngest players in our club, ages 4-6. We emphasize long term development: teaching basic skills, encouraging kids to have fun & develop a love for the game, developing a strong foundation for learning and understanding the material, and enabling kids to gain a good grasp of techniques that provide the stepping stones to play the game at a higher level in the future. Many players on our U8 to U13 competitive teams started soccer in our Academy program. We have a strong "club" model to promote this development, in which all teams, players & coaches collaborate and cooperate. Our highly qualified and licensed coaches have many years of coaching experience with all ages and levels around the world. All coaches have a strong commitment to teaching and sharing their passion for the game.

Club soccer for kids ages 8-18 in and around Palo Alto CA
The Stanford Soccer Club is a competitive youth soccer club serving Palo Alto and neighboring communities. Our teams compete in the Cal North – Cal Soccer League (CCSL) and NorCal Premier Soccer League across all competitive levels.

Unlike many clubs, the Stanford Soccer Club emphasizes parental involvement in virtually all aspects of team leadership. Professional coaches provide our players with outstanding training and skill development. But it is team parents--not the club--who make the key decisions regarding player selection, coach selection, and the competitive objectives of each team.

Our distinctive approach to competitive soccer has proven extremely popular in the Palo Alto community, allowing the Stanford Soccer Club to thrive and to grow to several hundred players today.

column8: The Excel Swim School is designed to introduce first-time swimmers to a fun and positive environment, as well as working with more experienced swimmers in developing and improving stroke technique. The swim school is a noncompetitive environment where the teachers’ goal is to empower the swimmer to improve to the best of their ability. The teachers are all Palo Alto High School Swimmers certified by Red Cross in CPR, First Aid, & Lifeguarding.

PASA was formed in the Fall of 2003 and welcomes swimmers of all ages and ability levels. PASA offers a program for everyone - from the beginner swimmer to the Olympian. 

PASA has been named a United States Swimming Gold Medal Club. The top 16 teams in the country receive this recognition. There are more than 2,800 USA Swim Clubs in the country, and PASA currently ranks as the 4th most competitive in the United States. PASA is ranked as the #1 team in Northern California.

The Northern Elite Water Polo Club is northern California's elite water polo developmental program. Specializing in the development of the entire individual, our focus has proven results time and time again.

Palo Alto Volleyball Club (PAVBC.com) is a community oriented, competitive volleyball club, founded in 2001 by Kevin Coleman, and based in Palo Alto. Jekara Wilson is the new Director and Head Coach.

The purpose of the club is to give girls an opportunity to learn to play competitive volleyball in fun, and local environment. We encourage girls to participate in multiple activities, volleyball being one. We believe well rounded student-athletes develop the skills needed to excel in many facets of life.

We offer clinics and recreation play for girls as early as elementary school, and we form competitive teams beginning in 6th grade. Our teams continue as long as there is a core group of committed athletes. Our club teams tend to be very successful, often winning tournaments and usually placing in the top tier of rankings by age groups.

Palo Alto Elite Volleyball Club is a non - profit, 501 (c) (3) corporation, dedicated to ; teaching excellent volleyball skills,learning the value of teamwork, and reinforcing the life lessons sports offer, including fun and family bonding.
